bt||cs|6|ht|b|fp|1|at|^-{           The 2@C Opening Bergen's Method          }
^-|FP||VA|4|AT|^B@2^*BMM: ^*NThis section is provided by Howard Schutzman. More on this topic at the end of this presentation by Tommy Solberg.|
PG| ***** 78 ***** |


cp|8|AT|

^B@2^*BHoward Schutzman: ^*N|cp||at|Marty Bergen uses the "4 and 4" rule when determining whether or not to open 2@C when your long suit is a major. The "4 and 4 rule" states you should open 2@C when your hand contains at least 4 quick tricks and has no more than 4 losers.|
PG| ***** 79 ***** |


AT|

Counting your quick tricks is easy. There are only 5 holdings you need to consider. AK = 2  quick tricks, A = 1 quick trick, KQ = 1 quick trick, AQ = 1.5 quick tricks, and Kx = .5 quick trick.|
PG| ***** 80 ***** |


AT|

Counting losers the way Bergen intended is more difficult. You do not use the common Losing Trick Count method to determine losers. You count what you expect to be your actual losers in the suit, based on an average length (with no high cards or help) in partner's hands. |
PG| ***** 81 ***** |


AT|

Sometimes counting losers is fairly easy. For example, if you hold AKQxxxx, that is no losers; since there are 6 cards out, on average partner will hold 2, so you will rarely lose any tricks in that suit. Even AKQxxx can be considered zero losers; with 7 cards missing, partner on average will have slightly over 2 cards in the suit, and with an 8 card fit, if the suit breaks 3-2, you will have no losers. |
PG| ***** 82 ***** |


AT|

As another example, Axxx is a  3 loser suit, because partner on average will have 3 cards in the suit, but a 3-3 break is not likely. You can consider AQ a half loser suit (you may or may not lose a trick depending on which defender  has the King). Similarly Kx is a 1.5 loser suit (which defender has the A determines whether or not you will lose 2 tricks). KQx is 1.5 losers (whether you lose 1 or 2 tricks depends on where+ the A is located).  KQ doubleton is one loser.|
PG| ***** 83 ***** |


AT|^B@2

^*BMM: ^*NEarlier Howard talked about the number of tricks. Here he used the same logic to determine the number of loser. Basically the same. Just saying it differently I take it. |
